Following first dose, only experienced fatigue and slight headache for one and a half days. Following second dose I experienced painful injection site for 2 days along with fatigue and generalized "out of sorts" for 2 days then felt quite well enough to resume normal activities and even took a 40 minute walk. That night (3/20) I had serious night sweats (fever?) and the following morning my arm at the injection site was hot and swollen and splotchy red,  my face was swollen on the left side (side of injection, and my left temple was extremely painful to touch. I had a slight fever (100.5) and experienced a period of horrible chills.  Later in the day my left eye became swollen and the area above my ear and eye and about one third of my forehead were bright angry red although the sensitivity of the temple had lessened. It was a Sunday and there was no walk-in clinic available so I contacted a Zoom style doctor through insurance.  She advised she believed it to be an allergic reaction and that I should go to an emergency room. I wasn't experiencing any breathing issues and was no longer feeling feverish and chills so decided to wait and see what the morning would bring. Monday am the redness and swelling had spread to the right side of my face and the areas behind both ears and down my neck so decided I should be seen. I had already come to believe these were swollen lymph nodes and the Physicians Assistant I was able to see diagnosed as lymphadenopathy.  The swellings and pain  receded over the next few days.  I still (4/1) have some stiffness in my left jaw and slight redness around my right eye above my ear.

Around 7 hours extreme fatigue set in. Chills hit at 9 hours. The headache became more generalized, extreme thirst, aches, shivering, and fatigue went on for exactly 24 hours. No appetite, rolling nausea (no vomiting), mental anxiety, cognitive fuzziness, sleepiness. Unable to read (short term memory and cognition), low attention for television. I never checked for fever. Around 6:30 the next evening (Sunday, 3/28), the symptoms retreated except for the fatigue and headache. Still a bit anorexic, but did eat lightly around 8 pm. Read, watched TV,  and slept better. Monday, March 29: I felt very fatigued and fuzzy-brained, but otherwise normal in the morning; the afternoon brought more energy, less headache. Tuesday, March 30: Everything  back to normal. Energy and clear thinking returned last.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: a 31 year old man who received the  COVID-19 vaccine on March 27, 2021 in the  Public Health Department parking lot. Upon arrival and check in, the patient declined any comorbidities and health history but did state that he was nervous. After administration of the vaccine by  NP, the patient lowered himself to the ground, from a sitting position, and had a 60 second tonic clonic seizure. Seizure precautions such as turning the patient on his side, supporting his head, and calling EMS were taken during the seizure. After 60 seconds, the patient came to and asked what happened. PPHD staff oriented the patient to what had happened, to which he proceeded to say ?oh that is normal for me when I get anxious.? With the help of PPHD staff and his wife, the patient was brought to a sitting position and given a granola bar and water to his request. According to clinic lead RN, ?his skin was normal in appearance for race, ethnicity, and age. He was mildly diaphoretic. He verbalized feelings of anxiety and worry surrounding the vaccine.?   As EMS arrived on the scene and began assessing vital signs the patients anxiety appeared to increase; he became less verbal, closed his eyes, and his breathing pattern became shallow. The patient then had a second seizure at this time lasting approximately 25 seconds. When the patient came to he immediately verbalized, ?I?m good, I?m good, I?m fine?. He was slow to respond to verbal cues, but persistently refused transport to the local acute care hospital for further evaluation. He rested on the ground in supine position for approximately 25 minutes, with his partner and EMS at his side. Upon further evaluation of the patient and his wife, it was determined that the patient has a history of seizure activities when he is nervous and that he was ?expecting? this to happen. The patient continued to decline medical care and transportation to the hospital. The patient left in medically stable condition with his wife operating the vehicle.

When I received the vaccine it seemed odd to me first because to me the needle was left in my arm longer than expected. This was my second vaccine and so I was familiar with it.  The first vaccine I had no adverse effects to.   It felt like the needle was left in and then maybe slightly pulled out then another drop injected.  When I got up to leave, I had a medicine type taste in the right corner of my mouth. The vaccine was given in my right arm.  Also I was injected high up on my arm, very close to my shoulder.   That day I was okay, but the following morning I was very thirsty and had no appetite.  I drank two tall glasses of water in the morning and had 1/2 piece of toast.  I also had a fever of 101.8.  I never get fevers!  I'm usually at around 96.8 to 97.   I then had chills during the day, and remained quite thirsty, and was also quite fatigued., with body aches, and a bit nauseated. I tried to eat something at 3 p.m. but still had no appetite so ate very little.   It seemed I craved carbs.  That evening I had French toast as my dinner, ate to slices.  I went to bed early and during the night I was sweating.  The next day (2 days after vaccine) I woke up with a terrible headache, again, I usually never get headaches.  It lasted all day. I took some aspirin, which did help.  I was still quite fatigued also.  By the 3rd day or so I was feeling better, but to this day I have body aches and pains, a bit of dizziness, nausea and fatigue.  My appetite has returned, though I don't eat as much.   I'm wondering if it was possible I was given too much of the vaccine?  I have not contacted my doctor at this point.  Hoping things will improve over time.

Received his first Pfizer dose (EL9262) on 3/10/21 and was given a Moderna second dose on 4/1/21 accidently. Has been informed on the incident. The clinic manager conducted the investigation and found that the event  was human error. The clinic process of keeping the vaccinations separate are in place. There are a list of Pfizer second doses on each table to ensure these individuals receive the correct vaccination. The nurse retrieved a Pfizer dose from the bag (away from Moderna) and placed it on the table and told the administering nurse this is a Pfizer second dose, here is the Pfizer vaccine. The nurse still picked up a Moderna vaccine from the other end of the table. The nurse noticed when the bandaid was being placed on his arm that the Pfizer dose was still on the table. When she inquired the administering nurse stated it was Moderna.  The clinic will speak to the administering nurse again to identify any barriers  and continue to evaluate the  processes to ensure this does not happen again.

Starting less than 24 hours after the second vaccine, I began having severe joint pain in hands, wrists, ankles, knees and elbows. Over the next couple days the severe pain improved however some mild joint pain persisted in the wrists, ankles and hands. Over the next 1.5 weeks the joint pain progressively worsened to the point that I could barely use my hands or sleep at night. I initially thought that the joint symptoms were still just vaccine side effects but since things were still getting worse 2 week post-vaccination I saw a rheumatologist on 1/20/21. He believed that my presentation was consistent with underlying inflammatory arthritis rather than vaccine side effects. Over the next couple weeks I had a thorough rheumatologic workup including extensive lab work and imaging, and was ultimately diagnosed with inflammatory polyarthritis with enthesitis with my triggering event for the initial arthritis flare being the second Covid vaccine. I was initially started on high dose prednisone (up to 60mg) and methotrexate with an upward titration but was unable to tolerate the medication due to side effects and lack of improvement in the enthesitis and have since started cimzia with plan to taper off of methotrexate. It is now 2 months since my initial diagnosis and my arthritis is controlled but I continue to have troublesome enthesitis in my hands and elbow.

Nothing definitive as to why he was so ill other then a viral infection.   We are not assuming or indicating it is vaccine related but we think it's worth noting.  Nothing in his routine had changed other then receiving the 1st vaccine.   No one at the hospital indicated it was related.

Patient received his Moderna #2 around 9:40 AM. About 4 minutes later his wife signaled that he was in distress by honking her horn. Upon arrival to the patient, he was clutching at his throat, wheezing, and whispering he couldn't breathe. Dyspneic with respiratory rate 20-30, heart rate 60's. No hives/flushing or signs of syncope. Given significant respiratory distress, decision was made to give epinephrine IM right thigh. About 4-5 minutes after injection, patient's respiratory rate came down and he said he felt his throat open up. He was then sent to the ER, where he received Benadryl, Famotidine, Methylprednisone, and Albuterol/Atrovent nebulizer. Pt sent home at 1PM, after 3 hours of observation. Pt is still doing well via phone follow up 24 hours after event.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 43 y/o man with significant for asthma developed lightheadedness and the sensation of an object in the back of his throat with swallowing about five minutes after getting his vaccine.  He denied difficulty breathing.  His initial vitals were 160/100, HR 100, O2 saturations 96%.  On examination, his tongue was not swollen and he had faint expiratory wheezing.  He was given 12.5mg of liquid benadryl.  He reported his symptoms slightly improved after five minutes of liquid benadryl.  His vitals were measured again about 20 minutes after his first set of vitals and his vitals were 150/100, HR 105, O2 sats 95%. He was given a second dose of 12.5mg of liquid benadryl.  After another 20 minutes, he reported that his symptoms were much improved.  On examination, his tongue was not swollen and faint expiratory wheezing was heard.  Last set of vitals were 140/95, HR 95, and O2 saturations 96%.  He calm and relaxed and was released.  He was told that he would not get his second dose with the current team due to the location being a non-clinical setting.  He was told to follow up with his PCM and/or allergist regarding if he should get a second dose in a hospital setting.

In fact, I felt so good that I went on a 12-mile bicycle ride. However, I began to experience diarrhea around 6:30 that evening. The next day I had headache, stiff neck, body aches, and a general malaise. The next day I had a rash all over my torso.  Those effects ceased, but on Saturday evening I broke out in hives on several areas of my legs, buttocks, and elbow. The hives were gone by the next day. The only thing that remains is a slight stiff neck. I never had fever, chills or any breathing problems. I spoke to my doctor the next day, and she was satisfied that I did not have any lingering symptoms or problems.

Post administration patient was discharged to observation by medical assistant to me. I was in the lobby providing break coverage. Patient presented with known COPD and Tremors. Patient had a slight cough when she initially sat down.    After about 5-10 minutes I noted that her respatory rate had increased and coughing had continued. I checked in with the patient and asked how she was feeling initially she reported some nausea no complaints of her breathing. I told the patient that I would be getting the provider just to check things out.    Onsite Provider agreed that patient should be brought to an exam room. Patient walked on her own to Exam room 3. Upon arriving in exam room 3, provider noted hives and arm redness instructed me to deliver Epi. 0.3mg Epi via auro injector was administered at 10:27 to the left thigh area. About 1029 patients breathing did get better. Patient remained alert and conscious. 1032 patient breathing became difficult again, ordered another round of 0.3mg Epi to the right thigh. 1033 breathing was feeling better, ordered patient to use her own Ventolin inhaler to help with some of the breathing problems.    1035 ordered 0.5mg of IM Benadryl, however paramedics arrived on scene and resumed care. Clinic Benadryl was not administered. Patient was transported to ER via Ambulance to hospital for further care.
LAB_DATA: Epinephrin 0.3mg autoinjector X2 given  discharged to EMS for ED Transport.

Suspected Vaccination failure; Acute respiratory infection; Influenza B virus infection; Cough; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of suspected vaccination failure in a infant patient who received Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden) for prophylaxis. Comparison of local influenza vaccine effectiveness using two methods. Vaccine 2021; 39(8): 1283-1289. DOI: 10.1016/j.vaccine.2021.01.013).   On an unknown date, the patient received Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden. On an unknown date, more than 2 weeks after receiving Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant), influenza b virus infection, acute respiratory tract infection (serious criteria GSK medically significant) and cough. On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure, influenza b virus infection, acute respiratory tract infection and cough were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure, influenza b virus infection, acute respiratory tract infection and cough to be related to Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of Suspected vaccination failure, in a patient aged more than or equal to 6-month-old of unspecified gender, who was vaccinated with Unspecified Influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to Table 3 reported in this literature article. The patient was a part of study that aimed at vaccine effectiveness (VE) estimates using methodology from the US Flu VE Network (research database) are compared with VE estimates using data from a clinical surveillance software system (administrative database). The advantages and disadvantages of both methods of estimating influenza VE are discussed. [The study took place in emergency departments, hospital-based clinics and outpatient primary and urgent care sites that are part of a large (40 hospital, 700 doctor's offices and outpatient sites) integrated health system]. The patient had not received antiviral medication in the 7 days before enrollment into the study. The patient belonged to administrative database group. No information on patient family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was reported.  On an unknown date, the patient received unspecified Influenza vaccine 2018-2019 season (administration site unspecified, dose not reported; batch number not provided). The age at vaccination was not reported. On an unspecified date, more than or equal to 14 days after vaccination, the patient presented with an acute respiratory infection (ARI) including cough within 7 days of symptom onset. Patient's respiratory specimen from nasopharyngeal and/or throat was taken for influenza virus testing by reverse-transcription polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR). The patient had emergency department visit and was diagnosed with Influenza B infection. [In this study, Briefly, patients aged more than or equal to 6 months presenting with an acute respiratory infection (ARI) including cough within 7 days of symptom onset were enrolled at participating outpatient healthcare facilities, including community physician offices, urgent care centers and emergency departments. Respiratory specimens (nasal and throat swabs from patients aged more than or equal to 2 years or nasal swabs only from patients aged less than 2 years) for influenza virus testing (including virus type and subtype) by RT-PCR. The influenza circulation period, defined as the dates between the first and last influenza positive research enrollment during each season, was determined for each year in both the administrative and research databases. The respiratory viral panels (RVPs) were performed on a nasopharyngeal swab. RVP tests might be conducted year-round, but were more routinely conducted in October through April on patients presenting with acute respiratory symptoms. For patients with more than one visit with RVP tests less than 14 days apart, only data from the first visit were included. The authors commented "In this comparison of influenza vaccine effectiveness estimates from a test-negative case-control research study and administrative data sources, subjects differed by demographic characteristics of age, race and site of enrollment. The administrative database included older patients, more non-whites and more patients enrolled in the emergency department. In emergency departments, research enrollees were younger, more often male and non-white, and VE against any influenza and all influenza A was significantly higher than was found in the administrative database. Whereas, in the outpatient clinics, age distribution was more evenly distributed in the administrative database and vaccination rates appeared to be higher than in the research database, but there were no significant differences in VE estimates. These differences may be attributed to the fact that recruitment for this research study was limited to two emergency departments (one a pediatric hospital) among several included in the administrative database and to a greater emphasis on research enrollment at urgent and primary care centers". The authors concluded "The selection of the appropriate method for determining influenza vaccine effectiveness depends on a multitude of factors. Among those factors is sample size, which likely obscured significant differences between administrative and research database VE estimates in this study except when limiting the analyses to the emergency departments. In this case, the research estimates were better. Differences in the types of persons enrolled in the databases, suggest that research estimates may be more generalizable. Other advantages of research databases for VE estimates include lack of clinician-related selection bias for testing and less misclassification of vaccination status because multiple sources are used. The advantages of the administrative databases are potentially shorter time to VE results and lower cost.". ECZTRA 5 (NCT03562377) was a phase 2, double-blind, randomized, placebo controlled, 30-week trial. Eligible adults were randomized 1:1 (tralokinumab 300 mg or placebo, 107:108 every 2 weeks [q2w] for 16 weeks), receiving Tdap (tetanus/diphtheria/pertussis) and meningococcal vaccines at week 12. Primary endpoints were positive anti-tetanus and anti-meningococcal responses (week 12-week 16; non-inferiority margin, -25%; responder, more than 3-fold immunoglobulin-G increase). The study enrolled patients with moderate-to-severe AD, aged 18-54 years, who were candidates for systemic therapy and had a recent (within 1 year) history of inadequate response to topical treatments or for whom topical treatments were medically inadvisable. Other key inclusion criteria included a diagnosis of AD for more than or equal to 1 year, AD involvement of more than or equal to 10% body surface area at screening and baseline, Eczema Area and Severity Index (EASI) more than or equal to 12 at screening and more than or equal to 16 at baseline, and Investigator's Global Assessment (IGA) more than or equal to 3 at screening and baseline. Patients were excluded if administration of either vaccine was contraindicated or medically inadvisable or if they had received any vaccine (except influenza virus vaccines) within 3 months prior to screening, any meningococcal vaccine within 1 year prior to screening, or any tetanus-, diphtheria-, or pertussis-containing vaccine within 5 years prior to screening. Patients were recruited from 11 sites in country and 35 sites in the country by the site's investigator]. [All patients randomized to tralokinumab received an initial loading dose of 600 mg on day 0 (baseline). At week 12, patients received one dose of combined tetanus, diphtheria, and acellular pertussis (Tdap; Boostrix) vaccine and one dose of meningococcal vaccine (Menactra), administered intramuscularly in the deltoid muscle of the upper arm (one vaccine in each arm), before tralokinumab or placebo injections, and in accordance with local labeling. [At week 16, non-inferiority of tralokinumab versus placebo for immune responses to Tdap (91.9% vs 96.1%) and meningococcal (86.0% vs 84.2%) vaccines was demonstrated. A positive anti-tetanus response was defined as having at least a three-fold immunoglobulin (Ig) G increase compared to week 12 if IgG less than or equal to 1.0 IU/mL at week 12 or IgG more than or equal to 2.5 IU/mL if IgG more than 1.0 IU/mL at week 12. A positive anti-meningococcal response was defined as IgG more than or equal to 3.0 mcg/mL with at least a three-fold increase compared to week 12, in three of the four assays used (for each meningococcal subtype included in the vaccine: A, C, W, and Y). Secondary endpoints aimed to assess the efficacy, safety, and tolerability of tralokinumab alongside vaccine administration, using the full analysis set. Upon completing the 16-week treatment period, eligible patients were invited to enter an open-label, long-term, extension trial of tralokinumab under a separate trial protocol (ECZTEND, NCT03587805); patients who used rescue medication in ECZTRA 5 were still eligible for inclusion in ECZTEND. Otherwise, patients were required to complete a 14-week, off-treatment, safety follow-up period. The rate of AEs, the number of moderate AEs, and the number of SAEs were higher in the tralokinumab group compared with the placebo group; this difference was driven by a single patient, in whom 18 of the 24 AEs were reported. The overall rate of AEs in the safety follow-up period was lower in the tralokinumab group versus the placebo group (69.59 vs 118.3 events per 100 patient-years' follow-up, respectively). Overall, 11 SAEs were reported in the safety follow-up period in four patients (two in each treatment group), with more events for tralokinumab (nine) compared with placebo (two). The higher rate in the tralokinumab group was driven by the single patient, in whom eight of the nine SAEs within the safety follow-up period occurred; five of these SAEs contributed to a fatal outcome for this patient. These results indicate that tralokinumab 300 mg every 2 weeks treatment did not affect the immune responses to Tdap or meningococcal vaccines, with vaccine-induced immune response rates within expected ranges. For both vaccines, the 95% CI for treatment differences were within the pre-specified -25% noninferiority margin, thereby demonstrating the noninferiority of tralokinumab compared with placebo with respect to immune responses to each concomitantly administered vaccine. In this phase 2 study, the treatment difference versus placebo was similar to that seen in the larger ECZTRA 1 and 2 monotherapy trials, further substantiating the robust efficacy reported at week 16 and over 52 weeks in these phase 3 trials. The results of this study indicate that tralokinumab's specific neutralization of IL-13 does not affect the immune response to concomitantly administered Tdap and meningococcal vaccines, suggesting that standard, non-live vaccines are effective and can be safely prescribed in tralokinumab-treated adults with moderate-to-severe AD without the need for tralokinumab interruption. Two of the vaccines were administered; Product contamination particulate matter; had particles floating around the solution after reconstitution; This case was reported by a other health professional via call center representative and described the occurrence of poor quality vaccine administered in a patient who received DTPa-IPV (Kinrix) (batch number HB7L7, expiry date 31st August 2021) for prophylaxis. This case was associated with a product complaint.   On an unknown date, the patient received Kinrix. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Kinrix, the patient experienced poor quality vaccine administered, product contamination particulate matter and pharmaceutical product complaint. On an unknown date, the outcome of the poor quality vaccine administered, product contamination particulate matter and pharmaceutical product complaint were unknown.  Additional details were provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The reporter stated that, the healthcare Center has two boxes of vaccine that had particles floating around the solution after reconstitution and two of the vaccines were administered to the patient, which led to poor quality vaccine administered, product contamination particulate matter and pharmaceutical product complaint. The office spoke to a GSK medical scientist liaison who advised that no additional doses be administered and the patients that received the vaccine should be re vaccinated. The reporter stated that, the pictures were being emailed for the address provided. The particles were white and the size was comparable to sea salt. The shape was like a rock with pointy edges. No additional patient information was provided. The case was linked with the case US2020156615 reported by same reporter.  Follow up information was received from Quality assurance department on 29th March 2021: Conclusions of the Quality assurance statements were received as follows: Customer reported a complaint which falls within the following product technical complaint category based on the defect description. A change of scope to was made as a consequence of the Quality Control analysis of the returned samples which identified the presence of white particles. The white particles have been identified as product formulation related particles, and, therefore are considered as inherent to the vaccine. Indeed, Kinrix vaccine is formulated with aluminum salt used as antigen carrier. In some conditions, the aluminum salt can aggregate and generate some small white particles. An investigation has been conducted, including review of the reported defect trends, the returned samples, the retained samples and our production records, which has demonstrated that the subject batch was produced in compliance with the applicable procedures and met all required specifications. Moreover, the in-depth investigation performed on raw materials and at all manufacturing steps has not identified any root cause which could explain the atypical number of inherent particles observed in the syringes. Since these particles are inherent to the vaccine and based on the investigation results, data trended and safety assessment, GlaxoSmithKline was confident that there is no risk for the patient. This complaint was considered as an isolated case. Therefore, GlaxoSmithKline Biologicals considered the complaint as substantiated.; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2020156615:Same reporter

On 07-JAN-2021, after receiving mRNA-1273, the patient's arm was swollen tender, and sore. The patient reported that the arm felt better the next day, after sleeping and taking it easy. The patient stated that on 08-JAN-2021, she woke up with more energy after sleeping and taking it easy. The injection site was not treated directly, but she may have taken some Advil for symptom relief. On 19-JAN-2021, the patient started not feeling well. On 20-JAN-2021, the patient noticed a red mark on their right arm where they had received the injection. The patient reported that she had a red rash on the right arm, below the injection site, that was hot to the touch. On 21-JAN-2021, she reported seeing a physician. The physician ordered an ultrasound to rule out a blood clot in the patient's arm. The doctor diagnosed the patient with cellulitis and prescribed an antibiotic (Doxycycline) and cetirizine hydrochloride. The event cellulitis was assessed as medically significant as per IME list. The patient reported feeling very nauseous and fatigued. The patient also reported chills and fever, chattering teeth, clammy hands and feet. The patient is still fatigued and nauseous but is starting to feel better today 28-JAN-2021. The treatment included an antibiotic (Doxycycline) and cetirizine hydrochloride.  Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Right side of mouth dropped; Diagnosed with paresthesia; Numbness in her cheek, tongue, jaw and head on the right side; Slurring; Blood pressure shot up; Bad headache; A spontaneous case was reported by a consumer concerning a 66-year-old female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 (mRNA-1273) vaccine and experienced the following: diagnosed with paresthesia (paraesthesia),  numbness in her cheek, tongue, jaw and head on the right side (hypaesthesia), right side of mouth dropped (facial paralysis), slurring (dysarthria), blood pressure shot up (hypertension) and bad headache (headache).    The patient's past medical history included stroke (she had stroke about 7 years ago). Concomitant products included blood pressure medication (not otherwise specified).  On 16-Feb-2021, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch no. 031L20A) intramuscularly in the right upper arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.     On 16-Feb-2021, within one minute after receiving the vaccine, the  patient experienced numbness in her cheek and tongue on the right side. The numbness moved to her jaw and head and she also had slurring. The right side of her mouth dropped, her blood pressure shot up, and she had a bad headache. The patient was taken to the emergency room (ER) and diagnosed with paresthesia and also treated for stroke symptoms. The patient was in the hospital from about 10:30-5:00 pm.  Treatment included aspirin and IV. The recommendation was made for the patient to take atorvastatin, but the patient was not taking it. The patient went to see her physician on 22-Feb-2021.  At the time of this report, the patient's side effects had not completely resolved.      The action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was unknown.   The outcome of the events, diagnosed with paresthesia, numbness in her cheek, tongue, jaw and head on the right side, right side of mouth dropped, slurring, blood pressure shot up, and bad headache, was considered not recovered/not resolved.; Reporter's Comments: Very limited information regarding this events has been provided at this time. The patient's medical history included diabetes. Products known to have been used by the patient, within two weeks prior to the event, included unspecified insulin.  On 11 Feb 2021, the patient received their first planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number: unknown) intramuscularly for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.   On 11 Feb 2021, the patient had a rise in her blood sugar (blood sugar 208, 212, 199 up until her bedtime of 9:45PM).  On 12 Feb 2021, the patient passed out on the kitchen floor and the patient's blood sugar took a dive (blood sugar was 304 9:00AM, blood sugar was 260 10:30AM  then stayed over 200/280 all day even with insulin). That evening, the patient experienced nausea and vomiting.   On 13 Feb 2021, the patient's blood sugar was up and had nausea and vomiting throughout the night. The patient spoke with her doctor, who told her to regulate it with insulin if she needed too. Per the report, the doctor informed the patient that there have been studies that say the vaccine has shown to mess with blood sugars. The patient's blood sugar remained between 144-179 all day even with insulin. The patient had nausea and vomiting.  On 14 Feb 2021, the patient reported still being sick. The patient reported a weight loss of 5 pounds and reported not being able to eat. Blood sugar was 174-292 all day even with insulin.  On 17 Feb 2021, the patient's blood sugar was bouncing between 53-151 all day even with insulin.  On 18 Feb 2021, the patient reported shortness of breath and was using Vicks to help clear the nasal passage.   On 19 Feb 2021, approximately at 6:00AM, the patient's spouse found patient breathing but unresponsive. At approximately 7:25AM, the patient died.  Treatment information included, unspecified insulin and Vicks.   Action taken with the drug in response to the event is not applicable.  The outcome of event, passed out on kitchen floor/loss of consciousness, was considered resolved on 12 Feb 2021. She said she had such severe fatigue that she goes to bed at 6:30PM every night and wakes up at 9:00AM the next day. She said her fatigue improved a little last week, but she had to take a nap after anytime she went to do something. Reported it had been 10-12 days since she had her second COVID-19 Vaccine, and she was still so tired. She is tired all of the time. Her tiredness was worse. She was tired and went to bed. She said the next morning she was tired, and then the next day she was really tired. She said the following day got so bad; she was in bed for 2 weeks. She said she only got out of bed to go to the bathroom and get something to drink and a few crackers to nibble on. She said she had such severe fatigue that she goes to bed at 6:30PM every night and wakes up at 9:00AM the next day. She said her fatigue improved a little last week, but she had to take a nap after anytime she went to do something. She said she had gone to her doctor yesterday and was exhausted when she got home. She said she didn't eat anything when she got home from her doctor appointment and went straight to bed. She said she woke up at 5:30AM today. Panic attack; Anxiety; Muscle spasms; Elevated blood pressure; Stress; Heart palpitations; Fatigue; Joint pain; Tingling (pins and needles) as if something was crawling on her right leg, left leg, right arm and left arm; Skin felt like it was burning; Numbness; Muscle weakness; This spontaneous case was received on 25-Mar-2021 from other non-health professional (consumer) via (reference number: SEQW21-01070) and concerned a female patient, of an unreported age.   The patient had no relevant medical history. The patient's concomitant medications included Flonase (fluticasone propionate) and not specified multivitamins, both used for an unreported indication. The patient never had reaction to vaccine before.   On 15-Sep-2019, the patient was vaccinated with Flucelvax Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, dose: 0.5 ml, anatomical location: right arm and route of administration: not reported). The batch number was not reported.  On the same day, three to four hours after receiving Flucelvax Quadrivalent, the patient experienced tingling and numbness. She had tingling (pins and needles) as if something was crawling on her right leg. Her skin felt like it was burning, and she experienced joint pain, muscle spasms followed by muscle weakness not so bad that she couldn't walk but would cause fatigue.  On 16-Sep-2019, the next morning (as reported), tingling continued in the right leg and started in left leg. Later that day, it was in both legs and left arm, then the feeling moved to the right arm. It was transient as she felt it was moving around her body.   On an unspecified date, the patient seen her primary care physician, rheumatologist and a neurologist.  On an unspecified date, the patient was seen in the emergency room for heart palpitations and elevated blood pressure and was diagnosed with panic attach due to stress. She was offered medication for anxiety, but she refused it, as she did not want to take this kind of medicine.   At the time of initial reporting on 25-Mar-2021, the patient had not recovered from events of 'tingling', numbness, 'skin burning', joint pain, muscle spasms and muscle weakness. The patient was still experiencing these symptoms, but they were not as severe.  The outcome of fatigue, panic attack, anxiety, blood pressure increased, palpitations and stress was not reported.   The patient did not provide causality assessment, but it was reported that all physicians felt that patient's reaction was caused by the vaccine.  Company comment: A female patient, of an unreported age developed hypoaesthesia, paraesthesia, skin burning sensation, arthralgia, muscle spasms, muscular weakness, and fatigue on the same day after vaccination with the suspect product, Flucelvax Quadrivalent. An unknown amount of time after vaccination the patient visited emergency room for panic attack, anxiety, blood pressure increased, stress, and palpitations. Information regarding the related diagnostic findings have not been provided. Due to lack of information regarding the temporal relationship, causality for the events panic attack, anxiety, blood pressure increased, stress, and palpitations is unassessable. Delivery at 36.6 weeks of gestation; Pre-eclampsia; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This observational study case received on 26-Mar-2021 from other health professional and concerned a 24-year-old, pregnant, female subject (subject ID: 002-0434) of body weight 175 lbs, height 66.3 inches and body mass index (BMI) 28, enrolled in CSLCT-OBS-17-15, a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcome in women immunized with Afluria QIV, a seasonal quadrivalent vaccine, during pregnancy.  The subject's concurrent conditions included increased BMI, anemia and the subject was carrier of beta thalassemia. The subject's concomitant medication included Prenatal plus DHA (unspecified vitamins and minerals plus docosahexaenoic acid) for pregnancy and anemia.  The subject's obstetrical history noted that the subject had one previous pregnancy with elective abortion. The subject had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations (MCMs). The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 27-Jun-2020, the estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 03-Apr-2021, while corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was reported as 04-Apr-2021. The type of pregnancy was singleton.  On 31-Aug-2020, ultrasound revealed no MCM.  On 29-Sep-2020, at gestational age of 13 weeks (calculated per LMP), the subject was vaccinated with Afluria QIV (Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL) (influenza vaccine; dose, anatomical location and  route of administration: not reported) (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation. The batch number reported was P100253284.  On 18-Nov-2020, ultrasound revealed no MCM.  On 10-Mar-2021, five months and nine days after receiving Afluria QIV, the subject developed severe pre-eclampsia.  On 11-Mar-2021, at 36.6 weeks of gestation (as reported), the subject delivered a female neonate vaginally with vacuum extraction. The neonate's birth weight was 1984 g, while head circumference was 31 cm and body length were 45.8 cm. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity and respiration (APGAR) score was 6 at one minute and was not reported for five and ten minutes. No MCM was identified at birth.  On the same day, the subject recovered from the event of 'pre-eclampsia'.  The outcome of the event of 'premature delivery' was not reported.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  The events of 'premature delivery' and pre-eclampsia were considered to be medically significant by a Physician.  This case is linked with the case 202102141 (the corresponding baby case).  Company comment: A 24-year-old subject was vaccinated with Afluria QIV at gestational age of 13 weeks. Five months and nine days after receiving Afluria QIV, the subject developed severe pre-eclampsia. At 36.6 weeks of gestation, the subject delivered a female neonate vaginally with vacuum extraction. The maternal concurrent conditions included BMI increased, anaemia and she was carrier of beta thalassemia. The maternal concomitant medication included Prenatal multivitamin + DHA (unspecified vitamins and minerals plus docosahexaenoic acid) used for pregnancy and anaemia.  The maternal obstetrical history included one previous pregnancy with one elective abortion. The neonate's mother had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations (MCMs). The neonate's mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. The paternal age was 26 years.   The maternal last menstrual period (LMP) date was 27-Jun-2020, the estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 03-Apr-2021, while corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was reported as 04-Apr-2021. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 31-Aug-2020, ultrasound scan revealed no MCM.  On 29-Sep-2020, at gestational age of 13 weeks (calculated per LMP), the neonate's mother was vaccinated with Afluria QIV (Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL) (influenza vaccine; dose, route of administration and anatomical location: not reported) (explicitly considered as 'Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation. The batch number reported was P100253284.  On 18-Nov-2020, ultrasound scan revealed no MCM.  On 10-Mar-2021, the neonate's mother experienced severe pre-eclampsia.   At gestational age of 36.6 weeks (as reported), the mother delivered female neonate, vaginally with vacuum extraction. The birth weight of the neonate was 1984 g, head circumference 31.0 cm and length 45.8 cm. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity and respiration (APGAR) score at one minute was 6, while scores at five minutes and ten minutes were not reported. No MCM was identified at birth.   The outcome of the events 'low birth weight baby', 'premature birth' and 'apgar score low' was not reported.   The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  The events of 'low birth weight baby', 'premature birth' and 'apgar score low' were considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus's Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  This case is linked with the case 202102140 (the corresponding mother case). SYMPTOM_TEXT: Arm felt itchy after the injection. Notably, it was not itchy at the injection site. Instead, it was itchy on the shoulder. The itching spread down to the inside of the arm, avoiding the injection site. About 10 minutes after the shot, the other arm started itching. We checked in with the pharmacist at the 15 minute mark and got the go-ahead to go home, since it was only itching.  On the drive home, about 20 minutes after the shot, the face and lips started itching. After arriving home, about 25 minutes after the shot, we noticed a small rash forming on the face. She took a benadryl and retired for the day, to be safe. The itching was still spreading about half an hour after the benadryl (60 minutes after the injection), reaching the back of her neck. However, the rash has improved since taking the benadryl and the face is less itchy. (She describes the itchy patches as moving to different parts of her body.)  It's currently only 65 minutes after the vaccine, so we're still keeping an eye on things! We wanted to report symptoms while they're fresh in mind.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received Pfizer Vaccine in December from the hospital, she then contracted COVID and was very sick 3 weeks later. There was no issue with the Pfizer Vaccine. The issue was she couldn't get the 2nd dose because she was actively sick with COVID.  She then went to a vaccination clinic at the local pharmacy where she received a janssen vaccine on the 31st of March. Again seems to be well tolerated at this time. However she received 2 immunizations that were different, not studied together, and not allowed per the EUA. The patient was aware it wasn't the correct vaccine, however they could not get the Pfizer vaccine as it is not offered in the area. So she opted to get the Janssen vaccine. It was pointed out to the individuals involved in the vaccination that this was technically not correct and needed to be reported to VAERS. At this time there are no health issues or concerns. We were just asked to report this.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Tuesday, immediately after injection, I experienced numbness in my left hand, which has continued off an on.  I attributed this to ongoing neck issues, so didn't think much of it, because I have it off and on. Numbness in right hand started about four hours after injection.  This caught my attention. Extreme pain and redness in left arm started about three hours after injection.  I could not use my left arm or lift it up.  I applied ice for 10 minutes on and off every 15 minutes for a little over an hour before going to bed.  It grew worse throughout the night. Fever started about six hours after injection and climbed to 101.1 before bedtime.  Fever vacillated between 99.9 and 101 for about 16 hours on Wednesday.  My neck hurt and I felt as if I had the full blown flu, but I couldn't sleep.  No appetite. Wednesday afternoon, I developed pain in the right wrist and weakness in wrist and hand.  It is painful to perform simple operations; for example, it is impossible for me to open a pop top can of soup.   Left hand weakness and pain developed today, Thursday morning; pain in right hand, but especially the  wrist, has worsened.
LAB_DATA: I have not reported the effects to my doctor; I am waiting to see if it subsides.  The fever is gone, and I am getting my energy back, but my right wrist is very painful.

Patient was given water, ice packs for the back of his neck and forehead, and ED was called. Patient stated he was feeling much better and did not need EMS, but due to store policy they were called. Patient relayed a history of fainting after receiving tattoos, that was not notated on his form. Patient remained on floor until EMS arrived about 20 minutes later and checked on patient. The pain traveled up my back until the evening when it settled between my shoulder blades and the base of my neck. The next day, my back and neck were stiff and painful. I called the doctor and he said it was likely that the spine was inflamed and should go away by day 5. The pain receded, but last night I noticed a very distended and bloated belly. SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient was screened and was found to have multiple medical allergies but no allergies to any of the components to the Janssen vaccine.  As a precaution, the nurses advised a 30 minute observation.  She received the vaccine without complication and then was being observed and they called me over and the paramedics were also with the patient.  About 17 minutes into observation, the patient started developing chest pressure (4/10), lightheadedness, and nausea.  No shortness of breath, stridor, diaphoresis, back pain, abdominal pain, vomiting, neurologic changes, and any signs or symptoms of anaphylaxis.  She was very anxious.  Further history revealed that the patient had been discharged from the hospital 6 week prior.  She initially went in for an abdominal laproscopic surgery and woke up to having 32 staples closing an abdominal incision.  They had to change from a laproscopic approach to an open abdomen approach due to complications.  She ended up with sepsis and a colostomy and was hospitalized for 2 weeks getting antibiotics.  She lives by herself and was overwhelmed before coming into the clinic for her vaccine.   The paramedics did a 12-lead ECG that showed sinus rhythm.  Vital signs and blood glucose were within normal limits.  The paramedics recommended that she go to the hospital to be checked out but she was very resistant and was tearful because she was traumatized from her previous hospitalization.  After some time, the paramedics convinced her to go to the hospital.  The paramedics hung around the emergency department and then came back once they found out that she was fine.

Patient is a 46-year-old woman with no known medical history who presents after receiving her 1 vaccine at the  Clinic on 4/1/21. She received her dose at 15:01. Patient drove to the second floor for post-injection observation. Around approximately, 1520, patient honked her car horn for assistance.  Subjective/Interval Events: - Upon arrival to patient's car, she was hyperventilating and appeared anxious, diaphoretic, warm, and clammy to touch on bilateral arms. She reported numbness and tingling in her bilateral hands, which radiated down to her lower extremities  - Within minutes, patient began hyperventilating more and crying out loud "what's going on?" We were able to calm patient down for a few minutes. Her resp rate decreased - Moments later, patient began reporting severe chest pain and left upper quadrant abdominal pain. - At this point, 911 was called at 1528. - Patient was transported out of her car into a gurney. - A second set of vitals was taken at that time. She was tachycardia to 180s. She attempted to vasovagal. This was unsuccessful as it was difficult for patient to follow commands given anxiety. - Shortly after lying on the gurney, EMS arrived. - Patient was placed on oxygen. Objective: Initial Vitals @ 1521; SBP 128/103; HR 129; RR 30s; Sat: 100% RA; VS @ 1528 136/110; HR 186; RR 32. Sat: 100% RA;  VS @1533 117/70; HR 130s; RR 40s; Sat: 100% RA; Initial assessment: Gen: Anxious, tearful, in acute distress, sitting in warm car with door propped open. Neuro: A/O x's 3; Cardiac: tachycardia ; HEENT: Airway clear, no angioedema, no oral swelling, no wheezing, no stridor. Speaking in short sentences with increased WOB, visibly using accessory muscles, hyperventilating. Bilateral upper extremities: bilateral arms warm to touch. Bilateral hands, cool, clammy, bilateral radial pulses present . Bilateral lower extremities: bilateral extremities warm to touch. MSK: MAE when transporting out of car into gurney. Sin: warm, pink, well perfused. No urticaria, not flushed. Plan: - Called 911 for cardiac workup, transported to local hospital for workup - Husband called and arrived on scene  - Charge RN notified. Patient was stable upon transfer to EMS.

I woke up throughout the night first night with left arm very sore feeling like an elephant trunk. In AM I woke up and felt ill. Throughout the day my temperature went up to 102 by the afternoon. I had headache, bad muscle pain and aches and generally felt miserable. Also, the gland under my arm pit was extremely swollen for 3 full days the size of a baseball. It hurt to rest my arm to my side. That second night, I took fever reducer before I went to bed. Fever broke and I soaked through 3 pairs of pjs. The next day my fever went up to 100.7. I didn't take any more fever reducer.  Third day it went up to 99.7. Fourth day normal temp but then I had extreme fatigue starting fourth day to where I barely had energy to sit up or even walk to the bathroom. I tried to do my online remote work that week but only worked 1/3 my schedule due to extreme fatigue. One day I was in the kitchen and had to drop to the floor and rest to get enough energy to walk back to my bedroom. The extreme fatigue lasted a good 5-6 days then the following week I pushed through my online work without reducing my hours but would go straight to bed right afterwards due to fatigue. I have struggled with Epstein Barr virus since I was 23 and get fatigued after getting strep or exercising too much or other illnesses so chalked it up to the EBV. I still had minor stabbing pain under my armpit until the past couple of days. My energy is now back to normal.

client complained of numbness to lip  after receiving the 1st COVID  (lot # EW 0150, exp. 4/3/21) at 1150. Client signaled PHN  and informed her she was starting to feel her left lip going numb, pressure to her lower base of the head and palpitations.  First set of vitals:blood pressure 140/80, pulse 80,  oxygen 98%. Client alert and oriented with flushed skin. Client denied shortness of breath , chest pain, no swelling at this time. PHN offered client Benadryl, per client would call friend first if medication was given so she could be picked up.  History of anxiety and hypertension, per client had an allergic reaction to flu shot in the past. Current medication: losartan.  At 1200 client stated numb sensation was radiating to left cheek PHN offered client Benadryl again and client accepted. 50 mg/IM Benadryl administered to right deltoid at 1203. Client informed we would keep her for further observation and would take vitals every 5mins. Vitals at 1205: pulse 94, blood pressure 180/95 oxygen 97%. Numbness to lip and face same, pressure to head same, palpitations same. Alert and oriented. Vitals 1210: blood pressure 120/80, pulse 81, oxygen 100%. Per client previous complaints improving. Client stated could feel cheek again. Vitals 1215: blood pressure 140/80, pulse 102, oxygen 99%. Client stated feeling nausea, emesis bag given and water. Per client also starting to feel drowsy. Palpitations improving and more sensation to lip area. At 1219 client stated having chills, palpitations returning. Per client was not sure if it was her anxiety. PHN offered 911, get paramedics for further assessment and to transfer to hospital for higher level care. Client refused, she felt benadryl was helping at this time. Vitals 1221: blood pressure 140/80, pulse 87, oxygen 99. Client stated all complaints improving. Vitals 1228: blood pressure 142/80, pulse 80, oxygen 100%. Vitals 1234: blood pressure 140/90, pulse 78, oxygen 99%. Per client lip and cheek no longer numb, normal sensation. Nausea had resolved and palpitations improving. 1241 vitals: blood pressure 140/90, pulse 80, oxygen 97%. Vitals 1247: blood pressure 130/90, pulse 75, oxygen 100%. Client stated feeling good. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Started feeling nauseous and woozy around 10PM so I went to bed. I woke up shortly after midnight to back pain and severe chest pressure, a migraine, and tingling and numbness all over my upper bod. My face was swollen and I could hardly open my eyes. I couldn't move my left arm (the arm I got the shot in) and within 20 min I couldn't really move much at all. I called 911 at 12:38am and they instructed me to use my EpiPen. I felt like I was going to pass out any second. My swelling went down and I was able to breathe much better after that, but was still unable to really move. I began shaking involuntarily, which the 911 operator told me was normal following the use of an EpiPen. I was able to slowly crawl to the front door. The paramedics checked my vitals but I don't really remember much after that. I think they lifted me onto a stretcher. The next thing I remember is being at the hospital. They did an EKG because I was still having heart pain (they said it was from the epi pen and would subside after 10 min but it just got worse). They also did some blood tests and an x-ray of my lungs. Everything looked good at that point. When they told me the results it was probably about 2AM. The doctor concluded that it was some sort of allergic reaction, although they emphasized that vaccine reactions usually occur close to the time of the shot.
LAB_DATA: 3/30 EKG, blood tests, chest X-ray, urinalysis. All looked good, the doc told me.
OTHER_MEDS: Birth control (Trinessa), Zoloft, Collagen, Daily Vitamin

All was well initially after receiving the injection on 03/15/21.  At 3:30 A.M. on 03/20/21, I was awakened from sleep by persistent itching.  I discovered light hives running along the inside of my right arm and along the right side of my torso, from the side of my right breast to my waistline.  I immediately took two (2) Benadryl capsules that we had in the house.  I also washed the hives with soap and water in case this was from an external source.  I had immediate relief from the itching and the hives immediately began to disappear, so I returned to bed and slept.  When I awoke in the morning at my normal time, I did not have any additional itching and there were no hives present anywhere on my body.  I went about my day and was at an appointment outside of the home when itching returned at approximately 1:00 P.M.  on 03/20/21.  This time it started on the outer side of my right breast and spread completely across the torso beneath both breasts within 45 minutes.  Also at 1:45 P.M., I felt a couple of episodes of light chills and "goose bumps."  When I arrived home by 2:00 P.M., I discovered that there were hives not only beneath my breasts, but also across the torso from one side to the other underneath the waistband of my jeans, as well as in a couple of random spots on my stomach.  I immediately took two (2) Benadryl capsules and took my temperature as well, which indicated a low-grade fever of about 100 degrees even.   I called at 24-hour Nurse Hotline, described my situation (including that the Benadryl I had just taken was immediately working on the new set of hives and itching), and was told to continue taking the Benadryl for a complete 24-hour cycle, as well as given information about what to watch for regarding the hives and instructed to obtain further medical help if the hives worsened despite taking the Benadryl.  Over the next several hours, the hives continued to recur (as well as the itching) and to spread throughout my torso and onto my back and arms.  I ended up in the Emergency Room after midnight when the Benadryl no longer did anything and the hives continued to worsen in both color and size.  I received an IV treatment of Benadryl, Prednisone, and Pepcid, and got immediate relief.  My heart rate reached 105 for a bit in the ER, but lowered to 95.  I had to continue taking these meds over the next several days at home, during which my hives eventually left some areas but spread down my legs to the tops of my feet before disappearing completely by 03/25/21.

I took an NSAID and eventually it improved the next day. I did have some arm pain in my left arm for a few days as well, but it was less bad than the pain that I get when I get the regular flu shot.

Death Narrative:  Pt passed away ~3 weeks after dose 1 of COVID vaccine (Moderna). Daughter was home with pt and after he went to the bathroom she reports pt was out of breath, however that has been chronic/ongoing for him due to his diagnosis of COPD, pulmonary HTN and metastatic lung cancer. After sitting and resting in a chair, she states patient became unresponsive. She called 911 who told her he had no pulse and was not breathing. She states that they were not able to resuscitate him. Pt had been suspected to be positive for COVID as he had symptoms of increased cough, congestion and rhinitis. Daughter (that is primary caregiver and lives in home with patient) tested positive for COVID on 1/31/21. She started having symptoms on 1/25/21. Patient started having symptoms on 1/31/21. No COVID test confirmed prior to pt's death. Patient had a definitive diagnosis of metastatic adenocarcinoma in October 2020. History of multimorbidity. He did have a 60 pack year history of smoking. Most likely cause of death from available records is metastatic lung cancer, with other serious diagnoses contributing.

covid+ Narrative: Patient with diagnosis of chronic respiratory failure with hypoxia secondary to COPD, dependent on oxygen/steroid, GERD, Rosacea secondary to long term steroid use, CAD, HLD, HTN, Diet controlled DM, Granulomatous disease of the lungs, Hx Abnormality Imaging of the lungs early 1990's- further imaging resolved without treatment, Vitamin D/B12 deficiency, Chronic rhinitis, Adjustment disorder with anxiety, Osteoarthritis of multiple joints. Patient admitted 3/19/21 with +COVID symptoms/test. Transferred to facility 3/27/21 with new onset Afib/further respiratory decompensation requiring NRB/Amiodarone gtt. Was made comfort care for Patient request and placed on MSO4 gtt. Patient passed away 3/31/21 at 1640 of Acute on Chronic respiratory failure secondary to COPD/COVID with daughter at side.

COVID+ Narrative:  Patient administered COVID-19 vaccine (Moderna) dose #1 2/18/2021. On 3/17/2021, Patient developed a cough and fever and was brought by ambulance to tertiary care facility with diagnosis of COVID-19. Patient on BIPAP as of 3/22/2021. On 3/26/2021, Patient was initiated on morphine drip for comfort care and BIPAP was discontinued. Patient passed away 3/26/2021.

ALS;weight loss;swallowing difficulties Narrative: Patient has a recent diagnosis of ALS. 2.5 months ago she felt that she was a neurologic baseline. She had the COVID vaccines (Moderna) on 1/31 and 2/27. She reports neurologic symptom onset after Moderna#1 and very rapid progression after Moderna #2. She denies F/C with vaccines and associates her symptoms temporally with the vaccines. She is awaiting diagnosis confirmation and has requested delaying PSG until later in April, but we can re-visit this if she prefers to do the study sooner. She also reports laryngospasm and we are initiating Q12 PPI to determine whether this improves her symptom.

RIGHT CHEST DISCOMFORT, HEART BURN, SHORTNESS OF BREATH, LEFT ARM SORENESS Narrative: A 61-year-old male with a history of sleep apnea, obesity, hypertension, CVA (7/2020) received his second dose of Moderna vaccine on 3/24/21, at approximately 11:26am. The patient received 1st dose of Moderna vaccine on 2/24/21 without complications other than sore arm. Per primary care provider, the patient developed shortness of breath and slight right chest discomfort on 3/25/21 while on short walk. Wife also reported patient's face hurt (like a pressure as well as soreness of left arm. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Had 2nd vaccine shot on 3/11, body aches and fever on 3/12, woke on 3/13 with excessive uterine bleeding, bleeding slowed in the afternoon, returned during the night into morning of 3/14, went to er. Received labwork and vaginal ultrasound, discharged and told to follow up with gynecologist. Contacted gynecologist on the evening of 3/15-Dr called in prescription for progesterin Took progesterin and bleeding continued. Saw Dr in office on 3/16-had 6+ hours of uncontrolled bleeding (using 5 super plus tampons and pads per hour. Dr prescribed Tranxemic acid-took until the afternoon of 3/18 when I contacted his office asking if the bleeding should have stopped. I was told to go the ER. I continued to bleed uncontrollably. I was admitted to Hospital - received 2 blood transfusions,  heart monitoring- on 3/19/21 I had emergency surgery for a cervical polyp. D&C /Polypectomy due to uncontrolled bleeding. Both surgeons   state there is no explanation and I could have died. I still have low hemoglobin and am going to receive iron infusions.   I am happy to supply lab work & results . This was an occurrence w/ no real explanation. It was very scary.
OTHER_MEDS: Zoloft, Topiramate, D3, Biotin, Probiotic, Turmeric, Vit C

I immediately notified the staff that I required a RN's assistance. I monitered the patient, and then asked my line leader (supervisor) to continue to moniter him as I had to continue vaccinating other patients. Patient was then directed to drive to the Medical survellance outside.

By noon (24 hrs after vaccine) I had low grade fever-100.2 with moderate to severe headache. I?ve always had migraines, this was not a migraine? Heart rate increased within 5 minutes of having the shot, went from 72 to 114.   My heart rate stayed at 109 or more until 10 PM the next night when its slowly went down to a normal heart rate.  At 3 am  (12 hours after the shot) i had  a blinding debilitating headache that lasted until 9pm the next night.   It also affected my vision.   The headache was so bad i could not concentrate on the simplest task.  I  was unsure of what i could take for the headache.   So, I did not take anything.    When i woke up i was very tired and this lasted until the following day.  6am i had a fever of 102.3 this went down to 100.4 at 9:15 pm that night. On Thursday, 4/1/2021, client received her first dose of Pfizer COVID vaccine (LOT # EW0150, EXP 7/2021) at approximately 10:07 am by vaccinator RN.  RN instructed client to self-monitored at the observation area. EMT found this 38 years old female in an observation chair sitting upright and requesting assistance. Due to the client needing translator, site manager present provided translation. lead RN came to assist EMT as needed. EMT reported client had a chief complaint of lightheadedness. Client stated that she felt like her head was "big" but that she did not feel like fainting. Client stated she had a history of high blood pressure and diabetes type 2 but did not take diabetes medication. Instead, she stated that she managed it strictly with her diet. Client had no known allergies. Assessment revealed no redness, hives, swelling, shortness of breath, chest pain or other signs of anaphylaxis throughout her body. Client denied having a headache but stated that she felt "hot" and that the heat was rising to her head. Client denied having a meal before her vaccination. Initial vitals were as follows: Alert and oriented x 4, Eyes were PERL (Pupils Equal and Reactive to Light) at 4 mm, pulse - 74, regular and strong at radial, O2 - 99%, blood pressure 160/98, Temperature 97 F,  Respirations 20 and regular. Skins were warm and mildly sweaty. Client consented to staying present for an extra 30 minutes after incident onset. Staff present verified that client had no food allergies and was provided food to eat while under observation. Client's vitals were monitored at 5 minutes intervals after the onset of the incident as follow: 10:18 am: 160/98 (Blood Pressure) , 74 (Heart Rate) , 99% (Oxygen), 20 (Respiration), 97 F (Temperature); 10:23 am: 162/98 , 68 , 99% , 18; 1028 : 162/98 , 68 , 99% , 18; 1033 : 162/98 , 72 , 99% , 18; 10:38 am: 162/98 , 72 , 99% , 18 , 98 F; 10:48 am: 162/98, 72, 99%, 18. Client reported at the end of her observation that she no longer felt hot and her head sensation was gone. Client's temperature improved from 97 degrees Fahrenheit to 98 degrees Fahrenheit and she ceased sweating at the end of her observation period. Client's husband was present and both were provided a Pfizer vaccine fact sheet and instructed to seek out medical advice or emergency care if a severe allergic reaction occurs later in the evening. Client left with husband in no apparent distress at 10:48 am with husband stating he would drive them home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Chills. Fever.   Can barely walk Nauseous Headache

At 9pm on 3/30/21 my left ear was red and very warm to the touch leading up to going to bed around 1030pm. The next day around 10am I felt a tingling in the lower left side of my face it felt like novocaine was wearing off after being at the dentist. My mouth and cheek were slightly numb. The next day I noticed that nothing had changed in my face but my left hand fingers were also slightly numb along with my left shoulder blade.  Arm was sore at injection site throughout. I went to see my primary Dr. at 3:30pm on 4/1/21 and after having me do facial exercises she said I had a mild case of Bell's Palsy and prescribed a steroid and an anti-viral since I had recently been sick the week prior.
LAB_DATA: None thus far but I am reporting this the day after I was seen by my doctor.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within four hours after vaccine administered I developed shaking chills, low grade fever, body aches, headache (lasted almost a week), and severe tiredness?all persisted for about 36 hours. By Tuesday, March 30 ( five days after vaccination), lymph nodes in my left armpit and along my neck on left side and in left groin area were suddenly swollen (to a noticeable degree under my arm, so much I thought initially it was a lump and needed to see my doctor) and painful. This lasted several days. I also suddenly began my menstrual cycle a full two weeks ahead of schedule?the same day as onset of lymph swelling.

Large (twice the size of a silver dollar) red swollen welt, extremely painful enough to keep me from sleeping for three days.  Then the pain subsided.  Still has swelling, patchy rash, very itchy.  It's been over a week and it doesn't look to be going away.  Very nervous to get the second shot.

Swelling or welt under both eyes. Blister-like bumps on swelling when I 1st noticed it, but they have lessened. But the welt is still there, and I feel the swelling more so now than I did last night. It's now been about 38 hours since receiving vaccine. It doesn't seem to be getting worse, aside from now being able to feel the swelling. Also, like I said, the blister-like bumps, on the welt/swelled area, have dissipated, so that got better. My face is also breaking out with acne since the shot. I do occasionally get acne break outs tho.
OTHER_MEDS: Ashwaghanda, Probiotic, Naturelo Men's Once Daily Multi-vitamin,
ALLERGIES: Minor allergies to strawberries, vanilla, dairy, mushrooms.

Bell's Palsy; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient). A 67-year-old female patient received bnt162b2 (BNT162B2), dose 1 intramuscular, administered in Arm Left on 03Mar2021 15:00 (at the age of 67years) as single dose for Covid-19 immunization. Medical history included hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, kidney disease, and known allergies to Penicillin and Sulfa drugs. Concomitant medications included amlodipine besylate (AMLODIPINE BESYLATE) and dulaglutide (TRULICITY); both taken for an unspecified indication, start and stop date were not reported. The patient is not pregnant at the time of vaccination. The patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19 prior to vaccination. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. On 19Mar2021 (13:00 Friday), the patient experience left side of face became numb and droopy with droopy eye lid and numb lips. The patient sought medical care; stroke was ruled out. The diagnosis was Bell's Palsy. Valacyclovir hcl 1-gram tab was prescribed. The adverse event resulted in Doctor or other healthcare professional office/clinic visit, Emergency room/department or urgent care. The patient has not been tested for COVID-19 since the vaccination. The outcome of event was recovering. The event was considered serious (seriousness criteria: important medical event).  Information about lot and batch number was requested.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Hypertension; Kidney disorder; Penicillin allergy; Sulfonamide allergy; Type 2 diabetes mellitus

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Shingles; Shingles/she was 7 years old she had her first shingles outbreak; burning sensation; They were flu-like symptoms; Diarrhea; Nausea; achiness; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable nurse (patient) from a Pfizer-sponsored program. A 43-years-old female patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE, Solution for injection, Lot Number: EN6203, Expiry Date: unknown), intramuscular, administered in the right deltoid (also reported as right arm) on 03Mar2021 16:00 at a single dose for covid-19 immunisation. Medical history included patient had anxiety all her life (ongoing), but reported 'started the medication about 10 years ago for the first time'; and patient had hypothyroidism, which she found out when she was going through the in-vitro fertilization. It was further reported that she was diagnosed with hypothyroidism when she and her husband were going through In-vitro fertilization and were having trouble conceiving and her TSH levels were off (date unknown). She didn't feel any different and didn't feel any different now since being on Synthroid; that was the only reason she found out. She was fairly healthy. Patient mentioned that when she was 7 years old she had her first shingles outbreak. Concomitant medications included oral levothyroxine sodium (SYNTHROID) taken for hypothyroidism at 75 ug, daily from an unspecified start date (approximately started 3 years ago) and ongoing; and oral sertraline hydrochloride (ZOLOFT) taken for anxiety at 50 mg, once a day from an unspecified start date (started about 10 years ago) and ongoing. The patient had no history of all previous immunization with the Pfizer vaccine considered as suspect. The patient had no prior vaccinations (within 4 weeks). Patient stated she do not want COVID and she is a pro-vaccines. Patient received first vaccine shot on 03Mar2021 and was diagnosed with shingles on the morning of 19Mar2021 and wanted to know if it was okay to take second dose of the vaccine next Thursday with active shingles diagnosis and being on antiviral medication, or should she wait. Patient stated that shingles, she was sure it was shingles, will not prevent her from getting second dose. She mentioned she was stuck, this was all new, and her doctor couldn't tell her because he didn't know. She was not sure what to do. She was not sure if she should delay getting the vaccine until she has stopped the antiviral medication, which she later clarified as Famciclovir. She stated initially her symptoms started Monday (Mar2021). They were flu-like symptoms on 17Mar2021. She was having diarrhea and feeling nauseated on 16Mar2021, thought coming down with the flu. On Wednesday (Mar2021), she felt pain, the shingles was on her buttocks. She went to the bathroom and saw red. Yesterday, 17Mar2021, she got a closer look because a burning sensation. When she looked closer, she realized it was shingles. It started more of a flu-ish feeling on Monday and noticed rash erupt on Wednesday. She also started to experience achiness on Monday (Mar2021). She was seen at her physician's office today, 19Mar2021 and was diagnosed with shingles this morning. The events shingles, nausea, diarrhea, flu-like symptoms and achiness were reported as not serious. The event burning sensation was reported as medically significant. Therapeutic measures were taken as a result of the events which included famciclovir, oral from 19Mar2021 and ongoing, at 500 mg, three times a day for shingles.  The patient had not recovered from the events burning sensation (reported as worsened), shingles (reported as worsened), nausea, flu-like symptoms, and achiness. The event diarrhea was recovering. The events diarrhea, nausea, achiness, and burning sensation were reported as unrelated to the vaccine suspect product.; Sender's Comments: The events burning sensation, diarrhea, nausea and pain are considered not related to BNT162B2, but intercurrent medical conditions. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

By late afternoon it had crept back up to 101. Still, I didn?t feel as badly as one would expect with a fever that high, even at 102.3, and was able to work from home until 5 PM. At 7 PM, with the 101 fever still persisting, I took my first dose of Tamiflu (and continued to take it as prescribed).  During the night, I could feel myself sweating. By morning the fever was gone. I have had no other adverse effects.

From physician note: Patient very pleasant 80-year-old female who presented to the hospitalist service with complaints of weakness and confusion after receiving second coronavirus vaccination.  Patient was confused overnight and then presented with blood sugar of 50.  During this hospitalization she received D5 normal saline in the emergency department with resolution of the hypoglycemia.  Her glipizide was held however with holding both glipizide and metformin her blood sugars became elevated in the 200-300 range.  Thus glipizide was restarted.  I did restart the glipizide at 5 mg twice daily however instead of the 20 mg twice daily she was taking at home.  Patient also reports that she recently has had weight loss that is unintentional.  She has a history of Barrett's esophagitis on an endoscopy which was performed in 2018.  In this regard she was seen by gastroenterology.  Plan is for an outpatient endoscopy and colonoscopy within the upcoming weeks.  Patient did have a CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis performed during this admission which revealed Stable abdominal lymphadenopathy from a prior scan, trace intrahepatic biliary duct dilatation and diverticulosis.  TSH was also sent and was within normal limits.  I did discuss with the patient the fact that she may benefit from being treated with Metformin plus an SGLT2 inhibitor or GLP-1 receptor agonist.  She will discuss this with her PCP.  I have also asked her to check her blood sugars 3 times daily for now.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had the first shot on March 1st.  My arm was a little swollen and sore for two days, and I was extremely tired, but other than that no adverse reaction.  I received my second shot on  March 19th, my arm again swollen and sore, and I could barely keep my eyes open the rest of the day.  On 3/20/21,  I woke at 8:30, feeling like I had hardly slept at all even though I had slept for 9 hours.  I woke up wheezing,  which led to me coughing and chills but no fever.  The exhaustion I had felt after the first shot, was nothing compared to this.  I thought it would go away, but it didn't.  I also noticed a lot for fluid retention in my lower legs and stomach area.  When I got on the scale, in the 20 days from the 1st shot til the day after the second shot I had gained 20 pounds of fluid.  I was stunned.  I could barely do a simple task, then I would have to sit down to rest for a minute, and would immediately fall asleep for 2 to 3 hours.  I went to my doctor's on 3/22/21.  They did a covid test, it was negative.  The doctor said I was definitely wheezing and gave me the only sample inhaler that they had in stock Anorro to try to open up my airways.  After a week, I was still having the issues, went back to doctor on 3/29/21 This time they perscribed 12 days of taper steroids.  I am on day 4.  I also received a referral to see a pulmonary specialist.  I am still dealing with the exhaustion, wheezing and cough.

Patient had received Covid vaccination and was seated in monitoring area. Patient was being monitored by nurse. She states patient complained of feeling lightheaded. Took off coat and drank some water. She checked his pulse at that time, and reports 60. She reported to other staff in area.  Patient explained that he has done this in the past with injections, but not always. He was sipping water, diaphoretic. At 0918 patient became was extremely diaphoretic, lips blue, eyes rolled back, and patient was unconscious, No pulse detected. I lowered him to floor from chair. EMT checked again for carotid pulse and I placed hands in position to start compressions. Faint pulse noted, and did not begin compressions. Nurse practitioner came over assisted by raising lower extremities onto chair. 0919 patient oxygen sats 91-93 percent.  Ambulance en route. Patient color improving, responding appropriately, alert and oriented. heart rate 51. blood pressure 112/59. 0921.
