SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine  Shot was given at 4:05 pm Wed 3/31. From then, injection site pain (by touch only) and arm stiffness increased that night. Thurs 4/1, pain and stiffness were worse, and it was difficult to completely move my left arm even though I was massaging the site and stretching my arm periodically. By Friday morning, the stiffness completely went away and it barely hurts to touch my left arm. When I went to go to sleep around 2 am Thurs, I had a fast heartbeat while laying down. I knew that was a possible severe allergic reaction but I had no other symptoms at the time other than the injection site pain and stiffness, so I went to bed. On Thurs morning around 11 am, I woke up in a sweat, so I'm not sure if I had a fever at all during the night. I did not think to check my temperature until that night around 10 pm. At that time it was 99.9 F. My head was fuzzy throughout the day similar to the flu, so it is possible that I had a low fewer or slightly elevated temperature. I do not have fever as of Friday morning when I woke up. My head is also not fuzzy anymore. Starting on Thurs morning and continuing throughout the day, I was extremely tired. I had two events to go to but did not have enough energy to get anything else done. This may have included slight muscle pain. This all disappeared by Friday morning when I woke up.
OTHER_MEDS: Strattera 60mg daily Desvenlafaxine ER 100mg daily Fexofenadine HCl USP 180mg daily Equate complete multivitamin adult, one daily N-Acetyl Cysteine 1200mg daily
CUR_ILL: Possible cold and/or nasal discharge from allergies

SYMPTOM_TEXT: To begin, I never, ever experience headaches and I never take Tylenol.  7 days after receiving the first vaccine, on the evening of the 03/31, I developed a severe headache.  It felt like a tightness around the perimeter of my forehead.  As the night went on, I took 1 table of extra strength Tylenol (Thank goodness my SO had a travel supply in his back pack) and went to bed.  The next morning I woke up with a mild headache and started working from home.  As the morning went on I developed chills, muscle aches, the headache got worse and I developed a dry cough.  Every time I coughed, it hurt my head.   After I drank 16 oz of electrolytes and took another tablet of extra strength Tylenol.  I started to feel better.  Went to bed, however, I was woken up at 1:45AM with the headache again and body chills.   When I woke up to start work, I still had the headache.   After eating breakfast, I took another tablet of extra strength Tylenol and drank more electrolytes.  By mid afternoon, I started to feel better.
OTHER_MEDS: Lisinopril 40mg, HCTZ 25 mg, Vit. C, Elderberry, Beet Root, Ca+ with Mg+, D3 and Zn, Move Free, Occuvite

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approx 4 minutes after the patient, received his Covid-19 Vaccine, he went to take a seat in his chair in the observation area. It was then witnessed by another patient, that Client had turned his head to the left looking "dazed" or "out of it" then fell to the floor. It was observed by other surrounding patients that he hit the left side of his head when he fell to the floor. I, RN, ran to his aide to find him turning to his right side and incoherent. Approx. 5 seconds went by until the patient came to and was able to talk to me and answer questions assessing his alertness. Another patient nearby was prompted by this nurse to call ED.The patients vitals were taken by the nurse and diaphoresis was observed from the patient. The patient stated he had "just felt sleepy and had not eaten prior to receiving his vaccine". His mother, was brought inside the buiding and stated that the patient had no prior health issues. This patient reported no pain to the head, neck or back but reported some dizziness prior to falling down. Patient stated that he remembers the entire event and did admit to losing consciousness for a short period of time. Fire dept and Paramedics arrived on scene at approx 5:56pm and assessed the patient. Vitals were taken and the patient refused to go to the hospital to be checked out. A juice box on site was given to the patient and the patient waited another approx 10 minutes before leaving with his mother to go home. Both the patient and the mother felt comfortable leaving the site.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Thursday, April 2, 2021 client DOB 8/3/1973 received her first dose of Pfizer COVID vaccine (LOT # EW0150, EXP 7/2021) at approximately 9:30am. During assessment of screening questions, client stated she has a history of severe allergic reaction to amoxicillin and was to be observed for 30 minutes in the Observation Area. At 10:00am, 30 minutes after vaccination, client approached EMT with chief complaint of "nausea and feeling light-headed". Vitals were taken on client at 10:08am: BP: 138/90, HR: 76 regular, strong, RR:14, O2 sat: 94%, A&O x4, pupils: PERRLA, skin: warm, pink and dry. Client requested to use the restroom and was accompanied to the restroom door by EMT. Lead was alerted and advised client when she returned to Observation Area to be observed for an additional 30 minutes. Client sat in the zero gravity chair while vitals were retaken. At 10:20am: BP: 142/94, HR: 70 regular and strong, RR: 13, O2 sat: 99%, A&O x4, pupils: PERRLA, skin: warm, pink and dry. Client stated to Lead RN & EMTs she has a history of high blood pressure which she takes medication for. Client also stated three weeks ago she went to the Urgent Care for vertigo. At 10:25am client stated her nausea had subsided and she was no longer feeling dizzy when standing up. Client stated she felt ok to drive herself home. Patient was alert and oriented x4 during entire interaction. No further interventions indicated. Client was educated by Lead RN & EMT on signs and symptoms of adverse reactions and when to go to the ED/call MD. Client was also encouraged to sign-up on v-safe. Client left vaccination site at approximately 10:50 with a steady gait.
CUR_ILL: 3 weeks prior went to Urgent Care d/t experiencing vertigo.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Six hours after receiving my 2nd Moderna vaccine, my blood glucose (BG) levels began rise more than usual. Since I'd just eaten dinner, I did not immediately deliver extra insulin. However, before going to bed, my BG level was even higher, so I delivered a corrective bolus using my Tandem insulin pump. I also use the Dexcom Continuous Glucose Monitoring System. Overnight, every time I woke up & checked my BG level, it was rising & rising, & so I continued to deliver corrective boluses. At 4:30 am this morning, I awoke, checked my BG level, & it was off the top of the graph on my pump; I used a fingerstick glucometer, & found that my level was 449, a dangerously high level. I delivered another corrective bolus, but my BG level would just not go down. I emailed my doctor, who instructed me to change my pump infusion site (I had actually done that about 5 hours following receiving the vaccine, but changed it again), delivered a 5-unit corrective bolus via syringe (shot) & checked my ketone level, finding that my ketones were extremely large, >160. I contacted the doctor's office again, & was instructed to consume a LOT of water, watch my BG level & check my ketones & inject 2- to 3-unit doses every hour. I did this all day today. By noon, my ketones had fallen to "negative" & my BG level had fallen to 169. It has continued to be a MAJOR struggle to keep my ketones in the negative range & my BG level anywhere near where it was prior to the Moderna vaccine. I don't know how long this will last, & I am AFRAID.
LAB_DATA: See in-home testing done by the patient, above. This has been ongoing from 4/1/2021 at 7:00 pm CST to the present, which is 4/2/2021 at 9:25 pm CST.
OTHER_MEDS: MEDICATIONS Humalog insulin delivered 24/7 via insulin pump; basal rate always ?dribbling in? & boluses delivered based on carbohydrate content of every meal; corrective boluses delivered if blood sugar is too high; typical daily total 36 u

SYMPTOM_TEXT: When it was time to mix the diluent with the pfizer vaccine, I was reading through the instructions and draw up the diluent. She drew up the correct amount of 1.8 ml and I checked it. As she was putting the diluent into the pfizer vaccine, a very small amount of the diluent spilled from the syringe and at the top of the needle. She put in the rest of the diluent and then we took the rest of what was left of the diluent and put it inside the the vaccine. When it was all mixed, it looked like we would have the correct amount. We withdrew 1 dose at a time with the correct amount. When we withdrew the the 4th dose, there was only a little bit left on the vial but not enough to give the 5th dose. I really thought there would be enough for 6 doses since we took the rest of the diluent that was left over and put it inside the vial which was 0.2 ml. I should of stopped what I was doing and called for help. I will take this as a learning lesson and will be more diligent in the future.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient complained feeling faint and felt like she was going to pass out. Patient was observed to have heavier breathing than normal. She also complained of numbness in her left arm. EMS was activated immediately. Patient's blood pressure was 51/38 mmHg . Oxygen was measured at 99 % Sp O2, PRbpm 45. Emergency contact for patient was notified. EMS arrived and took over. Patient returned hours later to pharmacy to informed us she was okay. She was told she had experienced vasovagal syncope.

On Friday, April 4, 2021 client  (DOB 5/3/1996) received his first dose of Pfizer COVID vaccine (LOT # EW0150, EXP 7/2021) at approximately 12:56pm. Per EMT report: at 1:06pm, client fell out of chair, landed on his left knee and regained consciousness immediately. Upon assessment, client stated his left knee pain was a 3 out of 10 scale. At 1:07pm, client was sat in the zero-gravity chair in supine position and given a bottle of water. Client stated he "felt pressure in ears-mainly right ear." EMT  & 2nd EMT coached client to breathe normally. At 1:09pm vitals were taken: BP: 120/70, HR: 52, RR: 10, O2 sat: 95%, skin: pale, moist, cool, eyes: PERRLA, LOC: A&O x4. Lead RN was notified and advised vitals be taken every 5 minutes for an additional 30 minutes. At 1:13pm vitals were retaken: BP: 120/70, HR: 69, RR: 12, O2 sat: 94%, eyes: PERRLA, skin, pale, moist, cool, LOC: A&O x4. On assessment, client stated he has no history of fainting, no allergies, and not taking any medication. Client stated he had a small amount of food and water intake and was not currently experiencing nausea. At 1:20pm, client stated the pressure in his ear subsided and was experiencing no headache, light-headedness or dizziness. At 1:25pm vitals were retaken: BP: 120/70, HR: 69, O2: 98%, skin: warm, pink, dry, LOC: A&Ox4. At 1:35pm, vitals: BP: 120/78, HR: 72, RR: 12, O2: 96%. Client was lowered to sitting position in gravity chair. No changes in vital signs were assessed by EMTs. At 1:40pm one final set of vitals were taken: BP: 120/76, HR: 66, RR: 13, O2 sat: 97%, eyes: PERRLA, A&O x4, skin: pink, warm & dry. At 2:15pm, client was able to safely stand up. No further interventions indicated. Client was educated by Lead RN & EMT on signs and symptoms of adverse reactions and when to go to the ED/call MD. Client was also encouraged to sign-up. Client left vaccination site at approximately 2:15pm with a steady gait. A family member was able to pick him up and drive him home.

After about 7-10 minutes I began to feel warm. The nurse asked me to remove my mask and I had a rash and hives on my neck, face and chest. I was taken to a room and given Benadryl and ice packs while my vitals were monitored. My ear turned bright read and burned so badly that they had to get ice for my ears as well. I was shaking and felt dizzy. After 15 minutes I was feeling worse and my ears were on fire. After listening to my chest the nurse called for an ambulance in case she needed to administer an epi pen. The ambulance arrived and I was taken out to be evaluated. This was around 40 minutes after being given Benadryl and it began to work. I was advised that being seen at the hospital would be a good idea but that all my vitals were back to normal but the rash and hives were still there. I decided not to go to the hospital and to see if the Benadryl continue to work. After about 1.5 hours after Benadryl my hives and rash have gone away mostly.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Fever and achiness
Last night (April 1), my lower hips and back started hurting (9/10). This morning when I woke up the injection site is raised, red, and warm to the touch.

The morning after the second dose, I woke up with 104 F temperature, chills, massive headache and pain at the injection site.  Took Tylenol every 4 hours all day long - fever, chills and headache did not stop.  Had to spend all day in bed, could not eat, had to get someone to take care of my children - literally could not stay awake or function.  Next day I woke up feverish and with a mild headache, Tylenol worked and I was able to function although I did not feel completely well.  At night the fever came back and also pain in the back of the neck.  Fever was not as bad as the day before.  Today, Woke up with headache, tylenol worked and I am functional.  No fever.    The pain at site injection is reseeding; it was sore and lymph nodes of arm pit are still swollen but it does not bother me.  The other symptoms were scary.
